2 Summary Statistics

  • relationBlueOneNorm: likelihood of causal relationship between box and bulb 1 (purple)
  • relationBlueTwoNorm: likelihood of causal relationship between box and bulb 2 (red)
  • exp1Norm: likelihood that agent expected bulb 1 (purple) to light up
  • exp2Norm: likelihood that agent expected bulb 2 (red) to light up
  • desire1Norm: likelihood that agent desires bulb 1 (purple) to light up
  • desire2Norm: likelihood that agent desires bulb 2 (red) to light up
  • knowledgeNorm: likelihood that agent has knowledge of the function of the box
ecl_dat$relationBlueOneNorm <- (ecl_dat$relationBlueOne - 1)/8
ecl_dat$relationBlueTwoNorm <- (ecl_dat$relationBlueTwo - 1)/8
ecl_dat$exp1Norm <- (ecl_dat$exp1 - 1)/8
ecl_dat$exp2Norm <- (ecl_dat$exp2 - 1)/8
ecl_dat$desire1Norm <- (ecl_dat$desire1 - 1)/8
ecl_dat$desire2Norm <- (ecl_dat$desire2 - 1)/8
ecl_dat$knowledgeNorm <- (ecl_dat$knowledge1 - 1)/8
human_cause_data <- gather.keep(ecl_dat, var.to.gather = c("relationBlueOneNorm", "relationBlueTwoNorm"), keep = c("id", "condition"), key = "structure",value="likelihood")

human_expectation_data <- gather.keep(ecl_dat, var.to.gather = c("exp1Norm","exp2Norm"), keep = c("id", "condition"), key = "structure",value="likelihood")

human_desire_data <- gather.keep(ecl_dat, var.to.gather = c("desire1Norm", "desire2Norm"), keep = c("id", "condition"), key = "structure",value="likelihood")

human_knowledge_data <- gather.keep(ecl_dat, var.to.gather = c("knowledgeNorm"), keep = c("id", "condition"), key = "structure",value="likelihood")
set.seed(100)

human_cause <- human_cause_data %>% group_by(condition, structure) %>%
  multi_boot_standard(col="likelihood")

human_expectation <- human_expectation_data %>% group_by(condition, structure) %>%
  multi_boot_standard(col="likelihood")

human_desire <- human_desire_data %>% group_by(condition, structure) %>%
  multi_boot_standard(col="likelihood")

human_knowledge <- human_knowledge_data %>% group_by(condition, structure) %>%
  multi_boot_standard(col="likelihood")

4 Visualizing Participants Inferences

4.1 Causal Inferences

The bar graphs shows participants causal inferences for:

  • the hypothesis the box and the purple bulb are causally related (blue bar).
  • the hypothesis the box and the red bulb are causally related (red bar).

The bar graphs on the left shows the mean likelihood ratings (normalized) of participants in the emotion condition, whereas the bar graphs on the right shows the mean likelihood ratings (normalized) of participants in the no emotion condition. Error bars represent 95% confidence intervals.

6 Hypothesis Testing

6.1 Causal Inferences

As expected, participants ratings on the causal relationship between the box and the purple bulb did not statistically differ across conditions. Participants relied mainly on direct observations to draw causal inference in this scenario and these observations support only one hypothesis.

t.test(relationBlueOne ~ condition, ecl_dat)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  relationBlueOne by condition
## t = -0.99768, df = 109.01, p-value = 0.3206
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group emotion and group no-emotion is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -1.1080209  0.3660189
## sample estimates:
##    mean in group emotion mean in group no-emotion 
##                 2.558824                 2.929825

As expected, participants ratings on the causal relationship between the box and the red bulb did not statistically differ across conditions. Participants relied mainly on direct observations to draw causal inference in this scenario and these observations support only one hypothesis.

t.test(relationBlueTwo ~ condition, ecl_dat)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  relationBlueTwo by condition
## t = 0.70764, df = 95.137, p-value = 0.4809
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group emotion and group no-emotion is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.3623838  0.7638286
## sample estimates:
##    mean in group emotion mean in group no-emotion 
##                 8.323529                 8.122807

6.2 Belief Inferences

On belief inference, participants in the emotion condition were more likely to infer that the agent expected the box to turn on the purple bulb (\(t(119.57) = 8.68, p < .001\)) than participants in the no-emotion condition. From the agents frustration, participants in the emotion condition inferred that the agent acted in order to turn on the red bulb.

t.test(exp1 ~ condition, ecl_dat)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  exp1 by condition
## t = 8.6799, df = 119.57, p-value = 2.376e-14
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group emotion and group no-emotion is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  2.890791 4.599405
## sample estimates:
##    mean in group emotion mean in group no-emotion 
##                 7.411765                 3.666667

Additionally, participants in the emotion condition were less likely to infer that the agent expected the box to turn on the red bulb (\(t(117.95) = -11.05, p < .001\)) than participants in the no-emotion condition. Participants in the no emotion condition assumed that the agents intended to turn on the red bulb (since there was no negative reaction to the outcome).

t.test(exp2 ~ condition, ecl_dat)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  exp2 by condition
## t = -11.051, df = 117.95, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group emotion and group no-emotion is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -5.071782 -3.530385
## sample estimates:
##    mean in group emotion mean in group no-emotion 
##                 3.014706                 7.315789

6.3 Desire Inferences

On desire inference, participants in the emotion condition were more likely to infer that the agent desired the purple bulb to be switched on (\(t(117.28) = 8.13, p < .001\)) than participants in the no-emotion condition. This is consistent with the belief inferences. The participants inferred that the agent intended to turn on the purple bulb in the emotion condition and conversely the red bulb in the no-emotion condition.

t.test(desire1 ~ condition, ecl_dat) # bulb1
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  desire1 by condition
## t = 8.131, df = 117.28, p-value = 4.968e-13
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group emotion and group no-emotion is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  2.289614 3.764050
## sample estimates:
##    mean in group emotion mean in group no-emotion 
##                 7.588235                 4.561404

On the other hand, participants in the emotion condition were less likely to infer that the agent desired the purple bulb to be switched on (\(t(116.78) = -10.40, p < .001\)) than participants in the no-emotion condition. Again, this is consistent with the belief inferences. The participants inferred that the agent intended to turn on the purple bulb in the emotion condition and conversely the red bulb in the no-emotion condition.

t.test(desire2 ~ condition, ecl_dat) # bulb2
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  desire2 by condition
## t = -10.403, df = 116.78, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group emotion and group no-emotion is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -4.747980 -3.229317
## sample estimates:
##    mean in group emotion mean in group no-emotion 
##                 2.941176                 6.929825

These ratings describe the non-normalized desire ratings collected on a Likert scale (from 1 to 9).

ecl_dat %>%
  group_by(condition) %>%
  summarise(
    desirePurple = paste0(round(mean(desire1, na.rm = T),2)," (",round(sd(desire1, na.rm = T),2), ")"),
    desireRed = paste0(round(mean(desire2, na.rm = T),2)," (",round(sd(desire2, na.rm = T),2), ")")
  )

6.4 Knowledge Inferences

Finally, with regards to knowledge inference, participants in the emotion condition were less likely to infer that the agent was knowledgeable about the function of the box (\(t(122.85) = -2.46, p = 0.02\)) than participants in the no-emotion condition. From the agents frustration, participants in the emotion condition perceived that he made a mistake and hence inferred that he is not highly knowledgeable.

t.test(knowledge1 ~ condition, ecl_dat)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test

These ratings describe the non-normalized knowledge ratings collected on a Likert scale (from 1 to 9).

ecl_dat %>%
  group_by(condition) %>%
  summarise(
    knowledge = paste0(round(mean(knowledge1, na.rm = T),2)," (",round(sd(knowledge1, na.rm = T),2), ")")
